The chamber was sized to be large enough for reliable combustion and small enough to save space. I selected a chamber pressure of 700 psi, intentionally higher than the main rocket engine's chamber pressure, to ensure the ASI could reliably drive flow into that high-pressure environment. 

Using NASA's CEA program, I inputted the initial conditions to derive the thermodynamic properties at the chamber, throat, and exit. From there, I hand-calculated the chamber, throat, and exit areas using [standard rocket propulsion equations](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1AZXSVgbvgGOOB4ZpcABzJtYAUtwhL6rn/view), which allowed me to derive each corresponding diameter. Two key design parameters drove the chamber geometry: contraction ratio and characteristic length. I set the contraction ratio high enough to provide enough room for a spark plug port, then adjusted the characteristic length to keep the chamber from becoming abnormally long. The contraction ratio I selected differs from values shown in literature to maximize combustion efficiency, but I overlooked this since I am not maximizing effiency.

